2.1. Eligibility criteria
We included in this meta-analysis studies that met the following 
eligibility criteria [1]: randomized studies [2]; comparing GLP-1 ago­
nists (liraglutide, lixisenatide, exenatide and NLY01) to placebo [3]; 
diagnosed less than 3 years earlier, who were receiving a stable dose of 
medications to treat symptoms, and who did not have motor compli­
cations); and [4] change from baseline in scores on the Movement Dis­
order Society–Unified Parkinson’s Disease Rating Scale (MDS-UPDRS) 
part III (range, 0 to 132, with higher scores indicating greater motor 
disability). We excluded [1]: overlapping populations, defined as studies 
with overlapping institutions and recruitment periods [2]; studies 
reporting no outcomes of interest; and [3] observational studies (cohort, 
case-control, cross-sectional, case series, and case reports), abstract-only 
publications, poster-only publications, and unpublished study protocols. 
There were no restrictions based on date or language of publication. In 
case of missing data from individual studies, the corresponding author 
was contacted for specific study results.
2.2. Search strategy and data extraction
We systematically searched for RCTs meeting the eligibility criteria 
in MEDLINE, EMBASE, and Cochrane Central Register of Controlled 
Trials databases, from inception to July 25, 2024.
The search strategy consisted of: ((lixisenatide OR exenatide OR 
NLY01 OR “glucagon-like peptide 1” OR “glucagon-like peptide 1” OR 
“glucagon-like peptide-1” OR GLP1 OR GLP-1 OR “GLP 1”) AND 
(“Parkinson’s disease”)).
The references from all included studies, previous systematic re­
views, and meta-analysis were also searched manually for eligible 
studies. The gray literature was not searched. The search was indepen­
dently conducted by 3 different authors (M.B.A. , D.G.M.F. and L.E.D.B. 
N.), who also independently extracted the data following predefined 
criteria for search and quality assessment. Disagreements were resolved 
through consensus.
2.3. End points
Outcomes of interest included: 1.MDS-UPDRS part 3 (off medica­
tion); 2.MDS-UPDRS part 3 (on medication); 3.MDS-UPDRS Global 
scores; 4.NMSS; 5.UPDRS-2 (on medication); 6.PDQ-39; 7.MATTIS DRS- 
2; 8.MADRS; 9.Levodopa.
2.4. Quality assessment
We evaluated the risk of bias of each study using the Cochrane Risk of 
Bias Tool for Randomized Trials 2 (RoB2). Two independent authors 
conducted a risk assessment (J.V.O.M and M.M.M.), and disagreements 
were resolved through consensus after discussing reasons for discrep­
ancy. The GRADEpro software (Evidence Prime) was used by 2 inde­
pendent reviewers to assess the quality of evidence for each outcome 
across the included studies. The GRADE (Grading of Recommendations, 
Assessment, Development, and Evaluations) criteria were used during 
the evaluation process.
2.5. Statistical analysis
We computed mean difference (MD) for continuous data with 95 % 
confidence interval (CI) applied as a measure of effect size. We consid­
ered P-values of < 0.05 to be statistically significant for our primary 
outcome. To evaluate heterogeneity, we used the Cochran Q test and I2 
statistics. I2 values < 10 % were considered negligible for heterogeneity, 
10 %–39 % low, 40 %–59 % moderate, 60 %–89 % high, and ≥90 % very 
high. To address possible variations in clinical and methodological as­
pects among the studies, we applied DerSimonian and Laird random- 
effects models in all outcomes regardless of I2 result for heterogeneity. 
Review Manager 5.4 (Nordic Cochrane Centre, The Cochrane Collabo­
ration) was used for statistical analysis.
3. Results
3.1. Study selection and baseline characteristics
Our systematic search yielded 966 potential studies as detailed in 
Fig. 1. After removing duplicates and studies that did not meet our in­
clusion criteria on title or abstract, 21 articles were fully assessed, as 
detailed in Fig. 1. Finally, after meticulous assessment, 5 studies were 
included, with a total of 484 patients, of whom 251 (51.9 %) were 
assigned to GLP-1 agonists [5–9]. The mean (SD) age ranged from 59.5 
to 63.5 on patients receiving GLP-1 agonists and from 57.8 to 64.2 on 
patients receiving placebo. The mean (SD) MDS-UPDRS part III off 
medications ranged from 14.8 to 32.8 on patients receiving GLP-1 ag­
onists and from 15.5 to 34 on patients receiving placebo. The mean (SD) 
Levodopa equivalent dose, mg, ranged from 317 to 973 on patients 
receiving GLP-1 agonists and from 355 to 977 on patients receiving 
placebo. Individual study characteristics are summarized in Table 1.
3.2. Primary outcome (MDS-UPDRS part III)
The GLP-1 receptor agonists had a beneficial effect, compared to 
placebo, in the change from baseline scores of the MDS-UPDRS part III 
(scale measuring motor disability) over 36–56 weeks. In the off- 
medication state, in a pooled analysis of 5 studies, there was a −1.22 
point between-group difference in motor score favoring the GLP-1 re­
ceptor agonists treatment (MD, −1.22; 95%IC -2,46 to 0,22; P = 0.05; I2 
= 49 %; Fig. 2A). GLP-1 agonists demonstrated statistical significance 
for the scores in the on-medication state improved by −2,52 points 
compared to the placebo group (MD, −2.52; 95%IC -4,02, −1,01; P =
0.001; I2 = 79 %; Fig. 2B).
3.3. Health-related quality of life outcomes (global and PDQ39)
We found statistical significance for the MDS-UPDRS Global score 
