change to baseline (MD, 3.43; 95 % CI, −6.38 to −0.48; P = 0.02; I2 =
43 %; Fig. 2C).
In contrast, the subjective ratings of quality of life PDQ-39 score 
change to baseline (MD, −0.91; 95 % CI, −2.22 to 0.39; P = 0.17; I2 =
72 %; Fig. 2D) showed no statistically significant difference between 
groups.
Also the UPDRS-2 score change to baseline (MD, −0.45; 95 % CI, 
−1.10 to 0.19; P = 0.17; I2 = 75 %; Fig. 2E) demonstrated no statistical 
significance between intervention and placebo groups.
3.4. Non-motor and cognitive outcomes (NMSS and MATTIS-DRS2)
We found statistical significance for the MATTIS-DRS2 score change 
to baseline (MD, 1.34; 95 % CI, 0.16 to 2.52; P = 0.03; I2 = 80 %; 
Fig. 3A), suggesting an improved cognitive performance compared to 
placebo.
In contrast, the NMSS score change to baseline (MD, −0.19; 95 % CI, 
−3.44 to 3.05; P = 0.91; I2 = 44 %; Fig. 3B) showed no statistically 
significant difference between groups.
