3.5. Depression and levodopa use between-group outcomes (MADRS and 
levodopa)
We found no statistical significance for both outcomes. GLP-1 ago­
nists was associated with no statistically significant difference with a 
mean difference (MD) of −1.04 in the MADRS change when compared to 
the placebo (MD, −1.04; 95 % CI, −2.57 to 0.48; P = 0.18; I2 = 0 %; 
Fig. 3C). Also the Levodopa use between-group did not show significant 
difference compared to placebo (MD, 2.77; 95 % CI, −34.10 to 28.57; P 
= 0.86; I2 = 46 %; Fig. 3D).
3.6. Quality assessment
The Risk of Bias 2 (RoB2) tool was used to assess the quality of 
included studies. A summary of the risk of bias assessment results is 
shown in Fig. 4. All the studies were rated at an overall low risk of bias. 
According to the GRADE tool, the overall certainty of the evidence for 
our primary outcome was assessed as high, based on the low risk of bias 
across all studies. The same assessment of high certainty applied to our 
secondary outcomes, with no significant issues regarding risk of bias, 
inconsistency, imprecision, or potential publication bias.
