4. Discussion
This meta-analysis of five randomized controlled trials (RCTs), 
encompassing 484 patients, provides an examination of the efficacy of 
GLP-1 receptor agonists in the treatment of Parkinson’s disease (PD).
By incorporating the last 3 RCTs published, we successfully quintu­
pled the patient population when compared to the last review [4]. The 
inclusion of NLY01 in subjects with early untreated PD(5) and Lix­
isenatide in patients also with early PD(6), in particular, significantly 
bolstered our statistical power.
The focus of this meta-analysis is to present a novel therapeutic 
avenue for managing PD. The findings indicate modest yet statistically 
significant improvements in both motor function and cognitive perfor­
mance when compared to placebo.
Although the results show statistically significant improvements in 
motor function and cognitive performance, it is important to emphasize 
that these improvements may be more indicative of symptomatic ben­
efits rather than definitive modifications in disease progression. The 
studies analyzed were not designed to test disease modification but 
rather to evaluate the effects of GLP-1 receptor agonists on symptom 
reduction in PD.
The primary outcome, evaluated through changes in the Movement 
Disorder Society–Unified Parkinson’s Disease Rating Scale (MDS- 
UPDRS) part III, demonstrated a statistically significant improvement in 
motor scores for patients administered GLP-1 receptor agonists. Notably, 
this improvement was evident both in the off-medication state and more 
prominently in the on-medication state.
The MDS-UPDRS III off-medication score was used as it provides a 
more accurate assessment of the baseline motor symptoms, without the 
influence of dopaminergic medications. The improvements observed 
with exenatide in the off-medication state may be interpreted as symp­
tomatic and prolonged effects, but not as definitive modifiers of PD 
progression. These results suggest that GLP-1 receptor agonists may 
enhance the effectiveness of existing dopaminergic therapies, poten­
tially acting synergistically to better manage motor symptoms in PD. 
This could be particularly beneficial in early-stage PD patients, where 
maximizing motor function preservation is crucial [10].
Moreover, the analysis revealed significant improvements in cogni­
tive performance, as measured by the Mattis Dementia Rating Scale-2 
(MATTIS-DRS2) scores. This suggests a potential neuroprotective ef­
fect of GLP-1 receptor agonists. Preclinical studies have shown that these 
agents can reduce neuroinflammation and promote neurogenesis, 
mechanisms that might underlie the observed cognitive benefits [3]. 
This dual action on both motor and cognitive symptoms could make 
GLP-1 receptor agonists a valuable addition to the therapeutic arsenal 
for PD, addressing two critical aspects of the disease that significantly 
impact patients’ quality of life [11].
Despite these encouraging results, the analysis did not find signifi­
cant differences in non-motor symptoms, as measured by the Non-Motor 
Symptoms Scale (NMSS), nor in psychiatric symptoms such as depres­
sion, assessed by the Montgomery-Åsberg Depression Rating Scale 
(MADRS). Additionally, there was no significant impact on the subjec­
tive quality of life, as measured by the Parkinson’s Disease 
Questionnaire-39 (PDQ-39) summary index. These findings underscore 
the complexity of PD and its multifaceted symptomatology, indicating 
that while GLP-1 receptor agonists may provide specific benefits, they 
may not comprehensively address all facets of the disease. This high­
lights the need for a holistic approach in PD management, incorporating 
therapies that target a broader spectrum of symptoms [12].
The absence of significant changes in levodopa usage suggests that 
GLP-1 receptor agonists may enhance motor function but are unlikely to 
reduce dopaminergic medication needs in the short term. These agents 
may be more effective as adjunctive therapies, potentially delaying the 
need for increased dopaminergic therapy. Variability in study designs, 
patient populations, and short follow-up durations limit conclusions on 
their long-term disease-modifying potential, highlighting the need for 
future trials with extended follow-up.
Regarding study design, it should be noted that these studies were 
not designed to assess disease modification. The lack of washout periods 
or crossover phases in the studies also limits the ability to adequately 
test the potential for disease modification. The focus of the studies was 
to evaluate the symptomatic effects of GLP-1 receptor agonists, which 
limits conclusions about their possible role in modifying disease 
progression.
The quality assessment using the Cochrane Risk of Bias Tool and 
GRADE criteria revealed consistently low levels of bias across all studies, 
indicating a high level of methodological rigor. Despite the overall low 
risk of bias, further research is necessary to validate the therapeutic 
potential of GLP-1 receptor agonists in Parkinson’s disease. Future 
studies should maintain these high standards of study design and 
comprehensive reporting to further strengthen the reliability of research 
outcomes.
An important consideration in these studies is that all were con­
ducted on Western populations, and ethnic differences could potentially 
influence the response to GLP-1 receptor agonists. Genetic, environ­
mental, and lifestyle factors may play a role in how patients of different 
ethnicities respond to treatment. Therefore, further studies are needed 
to explore the efficacy and safety of GLP-1 receptor agonists in diverse 
ethnic groups, ensuring that treatment recommendations are inclusive 
and appropriate for all populations.
