5 
Overall, this meta-analysis supports the potential role of GLP-1 re­
ceptor agonists as promising adjunctive treatments in PD, particularly 
for enhancing motor and cognitive outcomes. However, further research 
is needed to explore their long-term efficacy, safety, and impact on a 
broader range of PD symptoms. Large-scale, well-designed randomized 
controlled trials with extended follow-up periods are essential to 
confirm these findings.
5. Conclusion
In conclusion, while GLP-1 receptor agonists show potential in 
modifying certain aspects of PD, the observed effects on motor out­
comes, such as the MDS-UPDRS III, may be more indicative of symp­
tomatic benefits rather than definitive modifications in disease 
progression. Although these agents may have an a significant effect on 
improving motor and cognitive symptoms, there is insufficient evidence 
to confirm that they modify the progression of PD. The inclusion of more 
studies focusing on disease modification, longer follow-up periods, and 
more robust study designs, including washout periods and crossover 
phases, is necessary to confirm these findings and better understand the 
role of GLP-1 receptor agonists in modulating the disease.
Their integration into clinical practice will require a deeper under­
standing of their mechanisms of action, optimal dosing strategies, and 
patient selection criteria. Continued research efforts are crucial to 
elucidate their role in the complex therapeutic landscape of Parkinson’s 
disease, potentially paving the way for more comprehensive and effec­
tive treatment paradigms in the future.
